# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: funnel-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:funnel-charts/bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] A funnel chart displays values as progressively decreasing proportions amounting to 100 percent in total.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] The size of the area is determined by the series value as a percentage of the total of all values.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] Any funnel consists of the higher part called *head* (or *base*) and the lower part referred to as *neck*.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] A typical example of a funnel chart starts with the sales leads on top, then down to the qualified leads, the hot leads and the closed deals.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] A sales funnel chart can also be used to quickly communicate your organization's sales process to new members of the sales team or other interested parties.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] A funnel chart can be used to display Web site visitor trends.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] It is likely that the funnel chart will display a wide area at the top, indicating visitor page hits to the homepage, and the other areas will be proportionally smaller, like the downloads or the people interested in buying the product.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] Another example is the order fulfillment funnel chart with the initiated orders on top and down to the bottom the orders delivered to satisfied customers.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] It shows how many there are still in the process and the percentage cancelled and returned.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] Ideally the funnel chart shows a process that starts at 100% and ends with a lower percentage where it is noticeable in what stages the decrease happens and at what rate.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] If the chart is also combined with research data, meaning quantified measurements of just how many items are lost at each step of the sales or order fulfillment process, then the funnel chart illustrates where the biggest bottlenecks are in the process.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] Note that unlike a real funnel, everything that is "poured in" at the top doesn't flow through to the bottom.
[src:funnel-charts/funnel-chart] The name only refers to the shape of the chart, the purpose of which is illustrative.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:funnel-charts/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] A **Pareto chart** is a type of chart that contains both bars and a line graph, where individual values are represented in descending order by bars, and the cumulative total is represented by the line.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The chart is named for the Pareto principle, which, in turn, derives its name from Vilfredo Pareto, a noted Italian economist.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] Its purpose is to assess the most frequently occurring defects by category.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The left vertical axis is the frequency of occurrence, but it can alternatively represent cost or another important unit of measure.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The right vertical axis is the cumulative percentage of the total number of occurrences, total cost, or total of the particular unit of measure.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] Because the values are in decreasing order, the cumulative function is a concave function.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] To take the example below, in order to lower the amount of late arrivals by 78%, it is sufficient to solve the first three issues.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The Pareto Chart demonstrates a power law relationship between the rank of a quality issue and that issue's contribution to cost.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] This means one can find a linear relationship on a log-log plot.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The purpose of the Pareto chart is to highlight the most important among a (typically large) set of factors.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] In quality control, Pareto charts are useful to find the defects to prioritize in order to observe the greatest overall improvement.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] It often represents the most common sources of defects, the highest occurring type of defect, or the most frequent reasons for customer complaints, and so on.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] Wilkinson (2006) devised an algorithm for producing statistically based acceptance limits (similar to confidence intervals) for each bar in the Pareto chart.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] These charts can be generated by simple spreadsheet programs, specialized statistical software tools, and online quality charts generators.
[src:funnel-charts/pareto-chart] The Pareto chart is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:funnel-charts/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:funnel-charts/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
